		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2008 SI"></a><br><code>sle2008s/paper01</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>A Flexible Infrastructure for Multilevel Language Engineering</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ColinAtkinson.html">Colin Atkinson</a>, <a href="../profile/MatthiasGutheil.html">Matthias Gutheil</a>, <a href="../profile/BastianKennel.html">Bastian Kennel</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1109/TSE.2009.31">10.1109/TSE.2009.31</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The paper presents and prototypes a new modelling infrastructure that provides built-in support for multilevel modelling, i.e., workbench/tool support for language engineering.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Its core technical contribution is a metamodeling approach that supports multiple ontological classification levels beyond standard linguistic metamodeling.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It explicitly targets combining general-purpose and domain-specific language perspectives over the same models, which is a form of language integration/coordination.
</li></ul></li></ul>
